  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Ojus got its name in 1897 when Albert Fitch chose the Seminole word meaning “plenty” or “lots of” to reflect the area’s fertile soil.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ojus%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Henry Flagler’s railroad reached Lemon City in the 1890s, and depots along the line sparked the rapid growth of Ojus.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://en-academic.com/dic.nsf/enwiki/68212"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Ojus Elementary School and the Ojus Branch Post Office stand as living reminders of the community’s early civic life.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://en-academic.com/dic.nsf/enwiki/68212"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Ojus attempted to incorporate as a town in 1926, but a series of court rulings and voter votes ultimately dissolved the municipality by 1935.",
